                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d317">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13234: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-18T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 18, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 18—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>74. Following from Canton: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“October 16, noon. I am confidentially informed that there is strong
                            possibility of a separatist move by Southwest in November unless Chiang
                            Kai-shek unexpectedly again postpones Fifth Congress or compromises
                            acceptably. Such a move also forecast in pronouncement to the press by
                            Hsiao Fu-chen, who returned from Siam only 2 days ago, announcing
                            separate Congress in Canton. Chen Chi-tang at present apparently adamant
                            in his attitude towards both Nanking and Japan.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
